{"/service/ndnp/nn/batch_nn_ehrlich_ver02/data/sn83030272/00206539975/1913092101/0885.xml":{"full_text":"THE SUN, SUNDAY, SEPTEMBER 21, 1919.\nWILL STAGE PLAYS AT\nCHURCH CONGRESS\nMystery Drninn to B Feature\nof Kpiseopal Conven\ntion Here.\n350 QlBLfl IX TRAINING\nYoiiiiu Women Will Give Also\nImpersonations of Curious\nPeoples of World.\nMstcry plays produced In ft miniature\ntheatre will lie one Of I ho features f 'he\nKplscopal convention In this city, whlrh\nwill ho opened on rt. Mrs. Henry L.\nHobart In tho author. A now ply. \"The\n(it t ilt Tiall,\" II liclng rehearsed by young\npeople of Trinity parish.\nThree hUOdrod and fifty young women\nera III training, on life stage, outride of\ntho mystery piny, those young womon\nwill ItlVO impersonations of curious peo\nples of the earth and so .make mission\nfront s real ns possible. The thentte\nIn to I\" called livery where.\nHernia of Csmiulttrri.\nThe picsldent of the New York organ\nisation is Mls RtllabCth Dclatleld. Heads\n.,f OOtnmlttaOa Include Mrs. Hlchard l-vln.\nilrs. Augustus Ki Hand, Mrs. Stephen\nMaker. Mrs. Vernon M. Pavls, Mrs. J.\nMcKvven Ames. Miss Anne Clnrkson, Mrs.\n.1 RarmM Aldrleh, Mrs. David H. Greer,\nMrs. John Gre enough. Mrs. Henry W,\nMunfoe, Mrs ChOrlaa H. Hussoll and\nMi a Haley Flske.\nIIh Sara I'ayson of New Itochelle la\ntraining child ran for a Joponaoa play.\nStudents of the General Theological Sem\nInarv are to help In some of tho plays\nMrs. W. H. Hrlstow. Mrs. A. It. Gray,\nMrs B. C. Zahrlskle. Miss Katherlne lu\nHois. Mrs. K. S. Mardn. Miss Kllen Parks,\nMloi Dorothy tlordon King ami Mra.\nQoorga F. Hover are actively at work.\nSocial I tod era of many cities. Interested\nIn missions and Identified with tho Epis\ncopal I'huroh. have engaged accommoda\ntions at New York hotels, some of them\nfor a fortnight Albany and Boston will\nsend deputation!, From Baltimore and\nPhiladelphia at leaat five hundred will\nCOtno, It Is said.\nIn St Michaels parish hall. Ninety\nninth street and Amsterdam avenue, mls\nsinniuy I i i shops from all over the world\nwill toll tho women of their work.\nWill Kloot ftp Blahops.\nThis convention will elect half a doien\nmissionary Uishops. One of the new\nKisln'ps will ho. It Is said, for the canal\nzone, nnd a somewhat larger territory\nwhich is to he transferred from the\nChurch of KnRland.\nFollowing the services at tho Cathedral\non October 9. when women will put on\ntho altar about IfTk.OOO for missions,\nthere will be a mooting In Carnegie Hull.\nTwo organizations of women In the\nEpiscopal Church, apart from regular\nmissions, plan conventions. One is the\nGlrla' Friendly Society, which Is to meet\nIII St. Michael's Church on October 16.\nBishop Courtney, Bishop Brent and the\nRev. Dr. Barry will bo speakers. The\nother Is the Daughters of the King. It\nwill moot In St. Agnes Chapel In Ninety\nsecond street October t4 to 1.\nDEMOTED, HE PROVES ABILITY.\nPatrolman Lowered From- Defective\nForce Make Capture.\nWhen I'atrnlman Frank Allen, a de\nmoted detective, attached to the West\n100th street police station, brought to\nHeadquarter! yesterday Patrick Rellly.\nalias Boyle. 45 years old. a laborer, who\nis charged With murdering Mrs Margaret\nCooney of 111 QanOOVOOrt etreet on June\n87, he scored a point that may put him\nback on the detective force.\nPrior to June 27 Allen was n first\nprade detective, drawing double tho salary\nho now receives. After the murder of\nMrs. Cooney was reported to the police and\nAllen's assignment to the case, charges\nwere brought against him by Theodore\n(rant, why is now Serving ten years in\nprison with six others for conducting an\nI'ast Side fence. Grant said he had\nturned over soma property to Allen,\nwhich had not been dtllvcred to the\nproperty clerk at I fcadyuarters Allen\ndenied the charge, but the Headquarters\nofficials striped him of his detective's\nbadge and lowered him to the rank of\npatrolman.\nAllen kept up his search for the man\na Ills day off. which Is Saturday, and\nduring tho week, when he had a few\nhours to himself. Ha found that Reilly's\nwife was an inmate of the Manhattan\nState Hospital on Ward's Island and that\nhe was visited frequently by a woman.\nHy shadowing this woman he learned that\nshe was sending letters to a man named\nBoyle in Ramsey, n. J, Alien went to\nRamsey and later to Deposit. N. Y., where\nhe learned that Rellly had gone ot Adrian,\nN. Y, a week before.\nAllen went to Adrian yesterday, arriv\ning there after walking four miles along\nthe Kile Railroad. A short distance out\nside the town he saw Rellly working with\na Motion gang. He arrested him and\nbrought him to New York.\nRellly made the boast. Allen says, that\nJn another day he would have been safe\nin Canada.\nKLINE SWEARS IN HARTMAH.\nnemlads New Jade of Importance\nof \"the Poor Man's Court.\"\nMayor Kline administered the oath of\noffice yeBterday to austave Hartman,\nwhom he appointed Judge of the Municipal\nCourt, Wecond District, to fill out the\nterm of Ion Sanders, who resigned. The\nMayor said:\n\"Mr. Hartman. this Is a very responsi\nble office to which I am appointing you,\nand while I don't know you peranoally\n1 have heard so much that Is good of you\nfrom ao jnany sources that I feel sat\nIsned you will discharge the dutlea of the\noffice aatlsfactorlly. Tho court to which\nyou are appointed has to do with the\npoorer classes of the community. It haa\nbeen called the ioor man's court' and\nI am sure that you will deal with the\ncaaes brought before you with klndnaaa\nand sympathy.\"\nJudge Hartman Is the Republican nom\ninee for the place to whloh Mayor Kline\nappointed him. Ho will run againat\nAaron J. Levy, majority leader of the\nAssembly nnd chairman of the Assembly\nboard of managera In the Suiier Im\npeachment. DENIES DR. WHITE'S CHARGES.\nIt. O. Barak Give Ball In 00,000\nAlienation .Halt.\nPtHLADRLeHiA, Sept. 20. Robert O\nBursk. of the wholesale grocery firm of\nHowell A Bursk. who Is defendant In a\n$50,000 alienation ault brought by Dr. J\nLouis White of East Orange, N. J., ap\npeared before Judge Thompson In the\nUnited States District Court to-day and\nenUred 12,600 ball for hla appearance at\nthe formal hearing In October.\nBeyond entering a general denial to Utti\ncharges of undue friendship with Mfa\nWhite neither Mr. Bursk nor hla attorney,\nex-Mayor John Weaver, would discuss tha\ncase\nDr. While haa also named Robert I.\nCunningham of Pittsburg as corespondent\nin a divorce, ault begun at tho same Uaas\naa tho alienation ault.\nBOT SHOT BY DRUNKARD DUE\nIVnvlnn'a victim Had Helped Hloa\nllosse aaal Was Carina far Hloa.\nChorloo Xucka, 17 ears old. dlod yea\ntorday at the Swedish Hospital In Brook\nlyn from tho bullet wound In tho head\nInflicted tho prevloua night at Ma homo.\n742 Franklin avenue, by David Navlng,\nC years old, while drunk.\nNavlng waa a clerk In the towing de\npartment of the Pennsylvania. Railroad\nand had boarded for several yeara with\nthe Kuoka family. He was found In a\ndrunken condition by young Kucka on\ntho Eastern Parkway on Friday evening\nand aaalated to hla homo and to hla\nroom by tho boy, who started to go\ndownatalra for aome hot water to bathe\na cut In the man's forehead. Navlng\ndrew a revolver and ahot him In the hack\nof the head.\nIt waa Juat after Navlng had bean ar\nraigned In the Platbuah court yaaterday.\nthat word came from the hospital of young\nKurks's death. The prlaoner broke down\nand shrieked, \"Don't tell me he la dead.\nI loved Mm and I didn't know what I\nwaa doing. I haven't the slightest recol\nlection of having done It.\"\nHe was held for the (Irand Jury. Nav\nlng lost his job With the Pennsylvania\nRailroad laat Tuesday and at onra took\nto drinking, keeping It urj until the hoy\ndlacovered him.\nSCHWAB GOES ABROAD\nTO ORDER 10 ORE SHIPS\nBig Fleet to Fly Foreign Flag\nSteel Man Discusses\nBusiness Outlook.\nCharles M. Schwab, president of the\nBethlehem Steel Corporation, who sailed\nyesterday by the Hamburg-American liner\nImporator, said he expected to spend only\na week on the other side and that the\nchief object of hla trip was to arrange\nfor the construction of a fleet of steam\nships to transport Iron ore from Coqulmbo,\nChile, by way of the Panama Canal to\nthis port. Bach ahlp will have a carry\ning capacity of 16,000 tons.\nThe fleet will be one of the biggest of\nits kind on the seas. It will require two\nnnd a half yeara for the construction of\nten vessels. The contract will be placed\nwith foreign builders because they can\nbuild cheaper than American. The siitps\nwill fly a foreign flag, probably that of\nChile.\nMr. Schwab apoke a bit pessimistically\nof the business outlook, although he In\ntroduced his remarks with the declaration\nthat he was an optimist. He said \"I\nthink there will be a little recession In\nbusiness, due to the uncertainty over this\ntariff revision and the currency bill. Pend\ning the settlement of these questions there\nmay be a setback. I well remember the\nyear 1893.\n\"In the ateel business everybody Is.\nbusy, but running under orders taken\nduring the' year. On the average about\none-half of the steel men's ahlpments are\nof this nature. I believe a moderate re\nvision of the tariff will do no harm, hut a\nradical one will hurt, and will hurt the\nsteel trade, especially In the East. You\nmust remember that a ton of rails can be\nshipped as cheaply from Belgium to New\nYork as 1 can ship them from Bethlehem\nto New York. Thus under a radical re\nvision consumers In the West would have\nan advantage.\n\"It Is true that our surplus' product has\nbeen sold 1n Europe cheaper than In the\nI'nlted States, but that does not hurt the\nconsumer. It Is a recognised principle In\nbusiness that after the manufacturer has\nsold all the products ho can at home he\nmay sell abroad even at a lower rate to\npay the expenses of running full time and\nkeeping labor employed.\"\nThe Imporator took away a large quan\ntity of silver bullion shipped by Wells,\nFargo Co.\nIRISH CENSUS SETTLES WILL.\nsurrogate Proves Claims at Half\nBrothers' Relatives.\nA certified copy of the Irish census\nreturn for 1851 was relied on by Burro\ngale Fowler in deciding a claim by rela\ntives of one William Kennedy that they\nare entitled to share in the eatate of\nJohn F. Kennedy because William was\nthe decedent's half-brother.\nA sister ot Kennedy and other relatives\ncontended that William was not related\nto the decedent In any way and their\ntest. many was such that while Surrogate\nFowler said that he didn't believe delib\nerate perjury had been committed the\ntask of deciding the case was made em\nbarrassing because of the contradictory\ntestimony.\nSurrogate Fowler found by the Irish\ncensus return that the father ,of the\ndecedent had a son by a former marriage\nliving In his house with his second wife\nand her children, which had been denied\nby the wltneaaea. He decided that thla eon\nwaa the decedent's half-brother and that\nthe cenaua record 4a more reliable as evi\ndence than the interested wltneaaea.\nSTEAMER COLON HITS A SHOAL\nSticks a While on Shrewsbury Reeks\nbat Gata t I m harmed.\nThe Panama steamship Colon, in yes\nterday from Cristobal, stopped for sev\neral hours yesterday morning on a aand\nand silt covered shoal off the Jersey\ncoast called Shrewsbury Rocks, about a\nmile south of Sea Bright. She was com\ning In slowly In the misty darkness of\nthe early morning when she burrrped Into\nthe shoal.\nSome or her paaaengera were awakened\nby the Jar of her grounding, but were\nunconcerned, aa they thought aha waa\nanchorlnsr. Thtt .t.nm ii K...\nJersey caught the Colon's wireless an\nnouncement of her nllvht wont tn V.\ndaylight and helped to haul her off. A\nrising line assisted Mho came to dock\nundamaged.\nCant. Mowbrsv mmvm h arrueu\naix ahlp lengths from tho buoy marking\nme mioiii. wnicn ne oeueves nas been ex\ntended seaward by refuse dumped in tho\nneighborhood by scows and piled upon\nthe ledge by currants.\nLONG TO HEAD NEWARK POLICE.\nOnly Owe of Five Captains to Paaa\nCivil Service Examination.\nNewark, n. J Sent n Th.'ni.i.\nCivil Service Commission announced to\nday that Capt. Michael T. Long of tho\nFifth precinct waa the only one of the\nfive captains to qualify for the position\nof chief of police, to succeed the late\nMichael Corbett. Hla average was IU7.\nThe other captains all fell below tho 10\nper cent, mark required.\n-ine commission also announced the re\nsult of the examination for promotion\nfrom lieutenant to .nt.ln nw,i.,\nFrank W. Tulte finished first, Detective\nJoseph Cordano second, and Detective\nThomas J. Corbally third.\n15 HURT IN TRAIN WRICK.\nHock Island Paaaeagrer Cars 49a Down\nDeep Embankment.\nKansas Citt. Mn aw an\npaaaengera ware Injured -early to-day\nwhan tho eaatbound Rack Inland pas\nsenger train No. 40, carrying a heavy\nuna ui coioraao tourists Dound Tor East\nern homes, waa wrecked two mllea west\nof Manhattan, Kan.\nTha engines and eight care, left tha\nrails, two Pullmans and two coachea\nrolling down a twenty foot embankment\nCHURCH ON WHEELS\nMAY BE IMPORTED\nDevised by Father Vaujrhan, It\nHaa Been Very Successful\nin England.\nLOOKS LIKE FREIGHT CAR\nHas a Pulpit on One Side, and\nCarries Supply of Chairs\nfor Congregation.\nThis season haa developed something\nbrand new in churchea. The church of\nthe village green, with Its spire and Its\nbell, is no longer considered essentlsl by\nchurch efficiency engineers. The new style\ncame Into being In London this summer,\nsnd Is now under consideration for use in\nthis city.\nAmericans are familiar with the rail\nroad rare converted Into chapels, and\nhauled without charging freight and pas\naenger rates from atatlon to atatlon by\nthe western railroads. Baptists and\nRoman Catholics maintain such churchea.\nThe new style is In this line.\nThe Experiment la England.\nThe Rev. Bernard Vang ban. who has\nbeen heard In New- York, brought out In\nKim land last summer an automobile\nchurch, and has used It extensively In\nrural England in the Interests of Roman\nCatholicism. Protestant clergymen adopt\ned the Idea, fixed up a car and followed\nthe Catholic car from town to town.\nThere are In New York certain locall\ntlea where churches are needed, but where\nIt is considered unwise to build them.\nLack of funds prevents buildings In cer\ntain localities: in others the permanency\nof the field is questionable, or the de\nmand may exist only In certain seasons\nof the year. Tenta are not popular or\npermanent. The new church car, devised\nand used in London this season, may solve\nthe problem.\nIt Is a structure somewhat like a mod\nern trolley csr. very long. It looks\nrather like a freight car. with a door In\nthe middle of one side, none at the ends,\nand one window on either side of the\ndoor. There are no end platforms. but\nInstead there runs along one side a fairly\nwide platform.\nt arries Ita Own Palplt.\nIn front of the door the floor Is a bit\nwider and here Is u rail upon which the\npreacher leans as against a pulpit rail,\non one side there Is room for a small\norgan and on the other are seats for\nspeakers awaiting their turn.\nThe Interior serves for meetings of\nBible classes and for conferences, and In\nthe car are stored chairs and books. The\ncar Is run to some open space, where it\nstands as long as the attendance at the\nmeeting seems to warrant then It Is\nmoved to anuther locality.\nThe plan worked so well in London\ntills season that christian people are de\nsigning more of them. New York chris\ntian leaders, at work on the popular re\nligious uplift, are looking Into this new\nstyle church with a view to Importing It.\nMINERS' GRIEVANCES FEWER.\nt onrlllntlnn Hoard Una Italy HT\nCaaea la 3 Years.\nOnly twenty-seven formal grievances\ncame before the Board of Conciliation,\nestablished In 1001 to settle disputes be\ntween enlne workers and operators, during\ntho three years from April 1. 1909, to\nMarch 31, 1912, according to a report of\nthe board Just published.\nOf these twenty-seven grievances six\nteen were withdrawn, generally because of\nan agreement between the parlies after a\ndiscussion of the case before the hoard.\nIn one case an equitable price was fixed\nby the board for certain work In four\ncases there wns a tie vote. One griev\nance was referred to an umpire, two were\nadjusted hy mutual concessions and in one\nthe mlneworker complainant was uphold.\nThe board found It had no Jurisdiction in\none case and another was allowed to rest\nby agreement of both aides.\nOne hundred and fifty formal griev\nances were presented to the board in the\nfirst three yeara of Its existence The\ndecrease Is due to the fact that in acting\non the earlier grievances the hoard es\ntablished rules and precedents which pre\nvent the presentation of similar griev\nances. O'DONOVAN R0SSA GRAVELY ILL\nIrish Patriot, Now KB, In St. Vin\ncent's Hospital, Staten Island.\nDonovan Rosea, the Fenian leader,\nloflg exiled from Ireland, who was erected\nto the House of Commons while In prison\nunder a life sentence for \"treaaon -felony,\"\nIs at St. Vincent's Hospital. West New\nBrighton, Staten Island, and very 111. He\nIs 82 years old.\nMr. Rosaa had been 111 and confined to\nhis bed for three years when he was\ntaken to the hospital about two weeks\nago. His wife had become too 111 to care\nfor him.\nAn effort Is to be made to persuade her\nto let the aged Irishman be tranaferred\nto St. Vincent's Hospital In Manhattan.\nThe Staten Island Institution will not\nkeep patients Incurably 111, aa Mr. Roaaa\nla aald to be.\nAbout a year ago Juatices Ooff and\nCohalan of the Supreme Court raised\n100 among New York Judgea and law\nyera for the old man'a aid, and aome hun\ndreds more have since been collected by\npublic subscription.\nJUDGE'S WILL 8TANDS TEST.\nConrt Upholds Disposal of Estate\nMade By Jnstlee Stelnert.\nA decision by Supreme Court Justice\nDavla construing tha will of Justice Henry\nStelnert of Special Sessions In a ault\nbrought by tha executors waa handed\ndown yesterday. Justice Stelnert died\nFobruary i laat, leaving four sons and\nfour daughters, all of age except two\nsons.\nHe made hla will In ltOI, when four of\nthe children were under 21 and three of\nthe ethers were self-supporting. He di\nrected that his estate be used for the\nsupport of hla aona Walter and John and\nhla daughter Anna, then under ago.\nThe ault waa brought on tho ground\nthat the will waa void under the laws\nof the State because the estate waa loft\nIn trust for the thraa children. Justice\nDavla holda that Juatloe Stelnert had no\nIntention to create a trust fund during\nthe Uvea og tho three children and that\ntha estate, valued at about 140,000, goes\noutright to tho three children.\nCLAIMS 8V, FEET OF HOTEL.\nMra. Mary Olfoill Aaks $10,000\nFront Hevllle for Dae of Her Land.\nA ault was filed In tha Supreme Court\nyesterday against Loula C. Raegener,\nowner of the Hotel Seville, for 116,000 on\nthe ground that the foundation of tha\nhotel wall occupies 2 feet Inches of\ntha adjoining property at If and tl Madi\nson avenue, owned by Mrs. Mary O'Neill.\nMra. O'Neill alleges that the hotel wall\nwao built on part of her property secretly,\nand that ahe didn't know until laat May\nthai tha wall encroached on her land.\nShe aaya the encroachment cannot be\nremoved without endangering tha lateral\nsupport of tha hotel building and wants\n111,000 for the use of bar land.\nEDISON ALMOST WELL AGAIN.\nInventor Hopes to Be Bark la His\nLaboratory Wednesday.\nWasr OgANon. N. J Sept. 20. \"Yes, I\nam feeling all right again. The doctor\nInsists upon my staying In the house for\na fen daya yet or I would ho down In the\nlaboratory doing a little work.\"\nThis was the statement made by Thomas\nA. Edison at hla home In Ulenmont.\nLlewellyn Park, to-day. The \"wlsard''\nhaa loot aeveral pounds of weight and\nthe lines In hla usually full face show\nthat he has been through a alege of ill\nness. For the first time since he became III,\nnearly two weeka ago upon his return\nfrom a motor trip In New England Mr.\nEdison to-day apent some time In going\nover business matters at Ms home with\nWilliam H. Meadowcroft, his personal\nrepresentative, and Harry Miller, hla pri\nvate secretary.\n\"Mr. Edison will he bark at the labor\natory about Wednesday,\" aald Mr.\nMeadowcroft.\nWhep aaked If Mr. Edison would here\nafter work fewer hours each day Instead\nof eighteen, aa haa been hla custom for\nyears, Mr. Meadowcroft aald \"hard work\nla Mr. Edison's greatest hobby, It Is his\ngreatest pleasure In life.\"\nTO ASK GRAND JURY\nFOR TOMBS KEEPERS\nCommissioner of Correction Han\nFinal Plan to Increase\nForce.\nThe Tombs population did not drop\nyesterday because none of the General\nSessions Judges held court. They never\ndo on Saturdays, no matter how many\nprisoners are clustered In the Centre\nstreet Jail.,\n\"Couldn't they alt on Saturday morn\nings?'' was asked.\nFriends of the Judges replied that most\nof them had out of town homes or week\nend invltatlona which would prevent.\nSo the Tombs census, 7M parsons In\nItl cells in the morning, shows no diminu\ntion. It was reported that on account of\nMayor Uaynor's public funeral to-morrow\nonly Judge Roaalsky would hold court\nIn the Tombs there are now only ten\nkeepers at night. \"Ten keepers to 7M\nprisoners, and all played out at that,\"\nwas one guards description of the dan\ngerous situation on his side of the Bridge\nof Sighs. \"Do you wonder that If there\nwas a break everybody in the place could\nget out?\"\nCommissioner of Correction Patrick A.\nWhitney has arranged to have hla keep\ners go in a body before the Board of Al\ndermen on October IS. Then he will\nmake a las. effort to get enough money to\nhire sufficient keepers for the Tombs. It\nis a matter of Justice to the guards now\non duty, said the Commissioner, and a\nmatter concerning the safety of the Jail.\nNo concerted attempt to break Jail has\nyet been tried, but there have been doaena\nof Individual attempts. The arrangement\nof the prison is so bewildering and the\nplace is so crowded and the confusion\ncaused by hundreds of visitors ao great\nthat escapes are fairly easy.\nJudge Swann, who haa been holding\ncourt this week in place of the late Judge\nO'Sullivan, exprcta to iult now for a\nwhile. Judge Craln is due back to-morrow,\nor Tuesday at the latest, to take hla\nplace.\nAn effort may la- mad? to get acting\nGovernor Glynn to appoint some one In\nJudge O'Sullivan's place to serve until\nJanuary 1, when the Judge to bo elected\nIn November will take office.\nStories In The St'N on Tuesday, Thurs\nday, Friday and yesterday calling atten\ntion to the Jamming of the Tombs and\nthe three hours a day sessions of the\nJudges have aided in bringing aisiut\nseveral changes, it was said ycaterday.\nSince the publication uf the first story\nthe Judges have seen (It to sit afternoons\nand tho District Attorney has lengthened\nthe hours of h's staff. Roth enntUPM\nusually do not come until October. An\nextra Grand Jury has been arranged for\nOctober. Th-.i number of prisoners In the\nTombs changeable to General Sessions\ncourt has d-opped from 498 on TucmJay\nto 461 yesterday. The number awaiting\ntrial remains the same. The Grand Jury\nhaa materially reduced the number in the\nTombs awaiting indictment. That the\nnumber chargeable to General Sessions\nIs atlll excessive Is Indicated hy last year's\nnsures 43!) on September 20, as against\n401 of yesterday. The need pf an extra\nGrand Jury next month Is shbwo by the\nfact that 883 indictments are pending\nThese are the houra the Judges worked\nlast week\nJudge Mulqueen in Part 1. Monday,\nthree house and ten minutes Tuesday,\nthree hours and ten minutes; Wednesday,\nfour hours and 'flfty-flve minutes Thurs\nday, Bve house (afternoon sessions were\nbegun) Friday, four Uiours and five\nminutes. He averaged four hours and\nfour minutes nnd disposed of forty-four\ncases.\nJudge Roaalsky in Part 11. Monday,\nfour houra and thirty-five minutes Tues\nday, two home and twenty minutes\nWednesday four hours and fifteen min\nutes; Thursday, five botlra and twenty\nrtve mlnules Friday five hours and fif\nteen minutes He averaged four hours\nand twenty-two minutes und disposed of\nseven case.\nJudge Swan In Part 111 Monday, four\nhouae and fifteen mlnuti Tuesday, three\nhoura and flfty-flve minutes Wednesday,\nfour houra and ten minutes; Thursday,\nfour hours and thirty minutes Friday,\nseven hours and thirty minutes (two hours\nIn court waiting for a verdict). He\naveraged four houra and fifty-two mln\nutea and disposed of twenty-one cases.\nHIPP0DB0KE OWNERS SUED.\nInventor of \"Living Ballvl\" Aaks\nfor (lO.ooo.\nThe Shubert-Andaraon Company, which\nleaaea the Hippodrome, has been aued\nby Hatnuel H. Zula for 160,000 under a\ncontract by which Zula alleiea he waa to\nKi t half the profits of the Hippodrome for\none year. He aaya he contracted to build\na sun which would ahoot acrobats Into a\nnet and was to operate It for three years.\nHe aliened that In the third year he waa\nto set half the profile, eatlmated at 1 no. -000,\nand that after he operated (he gun\nfor two weeka tha defendants broke tha\ncontract.\nThe defendants say that the plaintiff\nhad an act called the \"Living Bullet,\" for\nwhich they .ware to pay IS50 a week If\nIt waa satisfactory. Thay aay they did\nnot uae the act because It was not up to\nexpectations. They ask that Zulu be\ncompelled to return ll.xfiO he cot for ma\nterials ta build the sun.\nAFTER LOOTED BANK'S DEBTORS\nHosevlllr Company 'a Director Proaa-1\nlaea ta Strennthen Nrcnrlty for Loss, j\nNewark, N. J.. Sept. 20. State llank-\nInn commissioner ueorKe i. L,a nionto nas\nreceived tha promise from one of the di\nrectors of the Rosevllle Trust Company\nwho was a heavy borrower from the\nInstitution to turn over to the bank ad\nditional securities 