on his way west and will\nsail from San Francisco at the end of\nNovember.\nPreparations are well advanced here\nand in Chlcugo for the $1,000,000 whirl\nwind campaign that la to make possible\nthe two Salvation Army training schools,\naa memorials of the Army founder. Tha\namount In hand ta about 1225.000.\nBLO0MINODALE BROS.' BIO WEEK\nTo Celebrate 4lat Anniversary of\nTheir Business.\nThe forty-flfsl anniversary of Blooming\ndale Bros.' department store at Third ave\nnue and Fifty-ninth street will be eele\nbruted from September 22 to 27. Since\nthe store was established at 93S Third\navenue it has grown and expanded. In\nacknowledgment and thanksgiving to Its\npatrons the management plana to hold a\nscries of special exhibitions of the features\nof the store that have been added from\nyear to year. All the departments will\nunite in these exhibitions and sales ta\nmake them memorable. Preparations\nhave been made to entertain large crowds\nof patrons during the week.\nBloomlngdale Bros.' store waa first\nopened by the late Lyman U. Blooming\ndale and his brother, Joseph H who were\nthe pioneers In the early uptown trade\nmovement. Their establishment In 1872\nwas only 20 feet wide and 60 feet deep,\nthree blocks below the present site.\nAlthough the firm started with limited\ncapital, the growth of the new shop\nquickly vindicated the Judgment of Its\nproprietors. Department after department\nwaa added and then the entire business\nmoved to the corner of Fifty-ninth street\nand Third avenue, extended from Third to\nLexington aVenue and Fifty-ninth to\nSixtieth si reet\nIn ls Joseph B. Blbomlncdale retired\nand Lyman G. Bloomlngdale became the\nsole proprietor. His three sons were soon\ndrafted for the service of the ever growing\nstore. At their father's death, on October\nMi 1. they were well fitted to carry\non the business and the firm became\nSamuel J., Hiram C. and Irvine I\nUltMimlngdale, Its present proprietors.\nAa the business of the store and Ita\npatronage increased the latest Improve,\nmerits In facilities were added to the es\ntablishment Many nw departments were\norganised and representatives aent to\n1'arls, London. Vienna, Berlin and other\ncommercial centres of Europe and too\nEvery department has\nprepared mountainous\nstocks of high grade want\ned merchandise, gathered\nafter months of prepara\ntion in the foremost mar\nkets of the Old World and\nthe New.\nAll that we can say to\nyou is to come to the store\nand attend this amazing\ndistribution of economies,\nfor never in the history of\nmerchandising have you\never seen such a collec\ntion of bargains under one\nroof.\nShoes, $1.95.\n$1.25 Juliettes, 95c.\n98c. Crochet Slippers at 59c.\nGirls' $1.98 Shoes, $1.69.\nMen's Lisle Socks, 8c.\nMen's Imported Socks, 121 iC.\nMen's Pure Silk Socks, 19c.\nWomen's Fine Silk Stockings, 49c.\nBoys' and Girls' Stockings, 8c.\n500 pairs Lace Curtains at 79c.\n$2.50 Tapestry Couch Covers at $1.69.\n$8.50 Marie Antoinette Curtains at $5.79.\n35c. Window Shades, 19c.\n79c Bolster Rolls, 59c.\n$22.00 Dining Room Suites, $14.75.\n$18.00 Dressers and Chiffoniers, $12.25.\n$15.00 China Closets. $9.95.\n$17.00 Oak Buffets, $11.95.\n$15.00 Brass Bed Outfit, $9.65.\n$30.00 Axminster Rugs, $24.50.\n$17.75 Brussels Rugs, $10.75.\n85c. Ingrain Carpets, 59c.\n90c. Brussels Carpets, 65c.\n35c. Oil Cloth, 27c.\n$1.10 Linoleum, 79c.\n$11.00 Dome Chandeliers, $6.98.\n$5.00 Tea Sets, $3.98.\n$1.50 Sugar and Cream Sets, $1.19.\n75c. Gas Lamp Outfit, 49c.\n69c. Table Damask, 49c.\n18x18 Table Napkins, 59c.\nRenaissance Table Cloths, $2.49.\n$1.75 Framed Pastels, 98c.\nFramed Pictures, regularly $2.25 and $2.75, at\n$1.59 and $1.85.\nAve., 59th to 60th St.-\nnKOOKM N A l FKTIst: M KTH.\nU R WISE\ntgW I I if you purchase your\nFurniture and Carpets\nat MASON'S, cor. of Bridge St. and\nMyrtle Ave.. Brooklyn, N. Y.\nOrient. Thouaanda of dollars have t r.\nspent on new service features within the\nlast few years, adding to tlte comfort of\nb